<font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="5"><b>Guardians of the status quo</b></font><p>
<font face="Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif" size="2">June 8, 2007 | Page 11</font><p>

<font face="Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif" size="2">Alexander Cockburn and Jeffrey St. Clair, <i><a href="http://www.amazon.com/gp/redirect.html?ie=UTF8&amp;location=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.amazon.com%2FEnd-Times-Fourth-Estate-Counterpunch%2Fdp%2F1904859372%3Fie%3DUTF8%26s%3Dbooks%26qid%3D1180988661%26sr%3D8-1&amp;tag=socialistwork-20&amp;linkCode=ur2&amp;camp=1789&amp;creative=9325" target="_blank">End Times: The Death of the Fourth Estate</a>. </i>CounterPunch and AK Press, 2007, 372 pages, $15.95.</font><p>

<font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>ALAN MAASS reviews a book on the media by the editors of CounterPunch.</b><p>

THE MID-1970s is often remembered as the "golden era" of American journalism. Most famously, the media exposed the crimes of the Nixon White House, reducing a president who had won re-election by a landslide two years before to a national laughingstock who resigned in disgrace before he was impeached.<p>
But Watergate was only one among many scandals during this period. Some of the darkest secrets of how government and business actually function in a supposedly democratic system were laid bare by a seemingly emboldened press.<p>

